    <title>a bit more origami</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhzh0UpzeYYkk-nz7_Evpb2x2X3qz0SV4sEhKx4muKnOGs9TwUMIE6bp5DJKxHCai_AIn0aGk9vvSQtsNx4rMoYO4F-D3LpUksyjdSy95ECegH32_D_sHxejtqGhpcSrbBZgAxcNzX5xS0/s1600-h/pent-knot.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhzh0UpzeYYkk-nz7_Evpb2x2X3qz0SV4sEhKx4muKnOGs9TwUMIE6bp5DJKxHCai_AIn0aGk9vvSQtsNx4rMoYO4F-D3LpUksyjdSy95ECegH32_D_sHxejtqGhpcSrbBZgAxcNzX5xS0/s320/pent-knot.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
This is just a footnote to an &lt;a href="http://mathrecreation.blogspot.com/2009/08/origami.html"&gt;earlier post&lt;/a&gt; on origami.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
There is a really nice &lt;a href="http://www.ted.com/index.php/talks/robert_lang_folds_way_new_origami.html"&gt;TED talk by Robert Lang&lt;/a&gt; where he explains why we like to use mathematics to solve problems (like, how to make paper bugs with legs): it lets us have dead people do our work for us. A bit more blunt than the "standing on the shoulders of giants" metaphor, but same idea. A similar talk is available &lt;a href="http://www.maa.org/news/070909lang.html"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;, courtesy of the MAA.&amp;nbsp;The &lt;a href="http://greenfusefilms.com/blog/"&gt;Between the Folds blog&lt;/a&gt; recently pointed out a nice online National Geographic &lt;a href="http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/big-idea/03/origami"&gt;article&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://blogs.ngm.com/blog_central/2009/09/confessions-of-an-origami-novice-i-fold.html"&gt;blog post&lt;/a&gt; on origami that touch on points that are developed a bit more fully in the Lang lectures.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Finally, here is a trio of great origami blogs: &lt;a href="http://origami.oschene.com/"&gt;The Fitful Flog&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://www.origamitessellations.com/"&gt;Origami&amp;nbsp;Tessellations&lt;/a&gt;, and&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://cedison.wordpress.com/"&gt;Student Flotsam and Origami Jetsam&lt;/a&gt;.</content>
